t9128.text: But how? What does it mean to be sincere and authentic? How can we be as sincere as possible, never dissemble or artificially shape our thoughts, statements, and self-expressions?

t9129.text: And when we look at the arts, it seems as if great artists became more and more sincere, more themselves, as their mastery grew. So, we resolve to be sincere.

t9130.text: So quite naturally we feel as if we have to shrug off this old, hand-me-down mantle and discover and express who we really are.

t9131.text: This impulse is especially strong for lovers of beauty who are newly adult. At twenty, we've been fed other people's opinions and ideas for decades, and even had to memorize them at school, to the point that the flood of information seems to drown our own authentic character.

t9132.text: So it's only natural that we extrapolate from our repulsion for insincerity, and conclude that sincerity is an essential component of aesthetic quality, both in human beauty and in the arts.

t9133.text: In the arts, insincerity makes us think of bad actors, characters and stories that don't ring true, or portraits that give a false impression of the model. They seem forced, they don't move us, and they make us distrust the authors, who are uninspired--or worse, propagandists.

t9134.text: We have good reasons to appreciate sincerity and authenticity. We like trustworthy people who don't put on airs and pretend to be other than they are.
